   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics">King Richard
                        III</hi>].<hi rendition="#sup">
                        <note>&quot;Remarks.&quot; <hi rendition="#italics">King Richard III. A
                              Tragedy, In Five Acts; By <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam"
                                 >William Shakspeare</ref>. As Performed at the Theatres Royal,
                              Drury Lane and Covent Garden. Printed Under the Authority of the
                              Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald</ref></hi>. London:
                           Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi
                              rendition="#italics"><title level="m">The British Theatre; or, A
                                 Collection of Plays, Which Are Acted At the Theatres Royal, Drury
                                 Lane, Covent Garden, and Haymarket. Printed Under the Authority of
                                 the Managers from the Prompt Books. With Biographical and Critical
                                 Remarks, by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                                    Inchbald.</ref></title></hi> In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. I. <hi
                              rendition="#italics"><title>Comedy of Errors</title></hi>. <hi
                              rendition="#italics"><title>Romeo and Juliet</title></hi>. <hi
                              rendition="#italics"><title>Hamlet</title></hi>. <hi
                              rendition="#italics"><title>King John</title></hi>. <hi
                              rendition="#italics"><title>King Richard III</title></hi>. London:
                           Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme, 1808. <hi
                              rendition="#italics"><title>Richard III</title></hi> was first staged
                           in London in 1591 or 1592. Laura DeWitt and Mary A. Waters co-edited this
                           essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The Criticism Archive</hi>.</note>
                     </hi>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______</title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p><ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref>&apos;s historical plays
               are particularly valuable, wherein faithful history is combined with transcendant
               poetry.</p>

            <p>The present play comprises every incident of note in the life and death of <ref
                  target="people.html#RichardIIIKingofEngland">King Richard the Third</ref>, and
               contains a period of fourteen years.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#MaloneEdmond">Mr. Malone</ref> says of this
               drama&#8212;&quot;From the many allusions to it in books of that age, when it was
               first acted, and the number of editions it passed through, I suspect it was more
               often represented, and more admired, than any of our author&apos;s
                  tragedies.&quot;<hi rendition="#sup"><note>See <ref target="people.html#ReedIsaac"
                        >Isaac Reed</ref>&apos;s 1803 edition of <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The
                           Plays of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                              Shakspeare</ref>, With the Corrections and Illustrations of Various
                           Commentators, to Which are Added Notes by <ref
                              target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">S. Johnson</ref> and <ref
                              target="people.html#SteevensGeorge">G. Steevens</ref></title></hi>,
                     vol. 14, page 526.</note></hi>
            </p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#ElizabethIQueenofEngland">Queen Elizabeth</ref>, who seems
               to have been a judge of theatrical, as well as political, measures highly admired the
               tragedy of <ref target="people.html#RichardIIIKingofEngland">Richard III</ref>. And
               it was played frequently by her royal command. </p>

            <p>Her majesty was ever most gracious to the author and all his productions; but it is
               by some critics imagined that her partiality to this drama, arose from the particular
               gratification, of beholding her grandfather, <ref
                  target="people.html#HenryVIIKingofEngland">Richmond</ref>,<hi rendition="#sup"
                        ><note><ref target="people.html#ElizabethIQueenofEngland">Queen
                        Elizabeth</ref>&apos;s grandfather, <ref
                        target="people.html#HenryVIIKingofEngland">Henry VII</ref>, was also Earl of
                     Richmond during his life.</note></hi> placed in the most exalted and amiable
               situation, in which <ref target="people.html#HenryVIIKingofEngland">Henry the
                  Seventh</ref> could ever be shown. </p>

            <p>In the reign of <ref target="people.html#WilliamIIIKingofEngland">William</ref> and
                  <ref target="people.html#MaryIIQueenofEngland">Mary</ref>, the whole first
                  <lb/><fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw>
               <pb n="4"/>act of this play was omitted in representation, by order of the licenser;
               who assigned as his reason&#8212;that the distress of <ref
                  target="people.html#HenryVIKingofEngland">Henry the Sixth</ref>, who is killed in
               the first act, by <ref target="people.html#RichardIIIKingofEngland">Richard</ref>,
               would put weak people too much in mind of <ref
                  target="people.html#JamesIIKingofEngland">King James the Second</ref>, who was
               then living an exile in France.</p>

            <p>Of this play, in representation, some peculiar circumstances may be observed. An
               audience, who, it is generally known, hate, even in the person of his representative,
               the villain of the drama, still hold in their greatest favour, the actor who performs
                  <ref target="people.html#RichardIIIKingofEngland">Richard the Third</ref>.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref>, <ref
                  target="people.html#HendersonJohn">Henderson</ref>, <ref
                  target="people.html#KembleJohn">Kemble</ref>, and <ref
                  target="people.html#CookeGeorge">Cooke</ref>, have all in their turn, been
               favoured with the love, as well as the admiration, of the town, for acting <ref
                  target="people.html#RichardIIIKingofEngland">Richard</ref>.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#WalpoleHorace">Walpole</ref>&apos;s &quot;<title>Historic
                  Doubts</title>&quot;<hi rendition="#sup"><note place="foot"><ref
                        target="people.html#WalpoleHorace">Horace Walpole</ref>&apos;s <hi
                        rendition="#italics"><title>Historic Doubts on the Life and Reign of <ref
                              target="people.html#RichardIIIKingofEngland">King Richard the
                              Third</ref></title></hi> (1768), a biography refuting the popular
                     image of <ref target="people.html#RichardIIIKingofEngland">Richard III</ref> as
                     a murderer. <ref target="people.html#WalpoleHorace">Walpole</ref> was the most
                     prominent of <ref target="people.html#RichardIIIKingofEngland">Richard
                        III</ref>&apos;s defenders.</note></hi> out of the question, <ref
                  target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref> appears to have been the actor, of
               all others, best suited for this character.&#8212;His diminutive figure gave the best
               personal likeness of the crooked-back king. He had, besides, if tradition may be
               relied on, the first abilities as a mimic; and <ref
                  target="people.html#RichardIIIKingofEngland">Richard</ref> himself, was a mass of
               mimicry, except in his ambition, and his cruelty.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#HendersonJohn">Henderson</ref> was received with welcome in
               the character, when <ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref> was no more;
               and <ref target="people.html#KembleJohn">Kemble</ref>, and <ref
                  target="people.html#CookeGeorge">Cooke</ref> have been followed on the same
               grounds. </p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#CookeGeorge">Cooke</ref> holds, at present, the possession
               of the part, and has popular favour in it, to the highest degree. That he is a very
               fine actor, all, who see him, acknowledge; but, of his performance of <ref
                  target="people.html#RichardIIIKingofEngland">Richard the Third</ref>,<pb n="5"/>
               it may exactly be said, what <ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Dr.
                  Johnson</ref> has said of the play of Richard the Third viz: <quote>This is one of
                  the most celebrated of our author&apos;s performances; yet, I know not, whether it
                  has not happened to him, as to others, to be praised most, when praise is not most
                     deserved.<hi rendition="#sup"><note><hi rendition="#italics">The plays of
                           William Shakespeare, in eight volumes, with the corrections and
                           illustrations of various commentators; to which are added notes by <ref
                              target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Sam. Johnson</ref><title/></hi>,
                        London, printed for J. and R. Tonson, H. Woodfall, J. Rivington, R. Baldwin,
                        L. Hawes, Clark and Collins, T. Longman, W. Johnston, T. Caslon, C. Corbet,
                        T. Lownds, and the Executors of B. Dodd, 1765, vol. 5 p.
                  362.</note></hi></quote><lb/><fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b
               3</hi></fw></p>
         </div>
      </body>
   </text>
